service: apmtraces
slug: scheduledquery
kind: ScheduledQuery
archetype: generated-service-manager
status/finalizer: required /
retain-until-confirmed-delete
requeue: provisioning, updating, terminating
provider states: create CREATING; update
UPDATING; delete DELETING
supported drift: definedTags, freeformTags,
scheduledQueryDescription,
scheduledQueryMaximumRuntimeInSeconds (+8 more)
reject before mutate: force-new fields
apmDomainId
create-only fields: none
list lookup: oci_apm_traces_scheduled_queries
filters apmDomainId, displayName; exact
scheduledQueryName unique match in ACTIVE,
CREATING, or UPDATING; duplicate matches fail
conflicts: none
open gaps: drift-guard
Reviewed lifecycle mapping treats CREATING as
provisioning, UPDATING as updating, ACTIVE as
success, and DELETING as terminating; FAILED is
terminal and DELETED is only a
delete-confirmation target.
Pre-create reuse always scopes by apmDomainId
and uses the SDK displayName filter from
spec.scheduledQueryName, but adoption still
requires a unique exact-name match from the list
summary surface.
Create and update return the ScheduledQuery body
directly, while delete returns headers only. The
runtime stays lifecycle-based and relies on
read-after-write plus confirm-delete rereads
instead of work-request polling.
status.apmDomainId mirrors the bound request
domain because OCI does not echo that query
parameter back on ScheduledQuery or
ScheduledQuerySummary.
Explicit clear-to-empty intent for zero-value
top-level fields remains a current gap until the
generated spec preserves empty-string, zero, and
empty-map updates distinctly from omission.
end note
note right of delete_pending
delete policy: required
delete observe: GetScheduledQuery or
ListScheduledQueries
delete targets: DELETED
end note
